          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "Here’s how this lines up with **this repo** and a typical Supabase setup.\n\n### Git-ai HTTP client: no separate `API_KEY`\n\n`ApiContext` only attaches the stored login token as a Bearer header. There is no parallel “API key” on outbound requests:\n\n```187:189:src/api/client.rs\n        if let Some(token) = &self.auth_token {\n            request = request.set(\"Authorization\", &format!(\"Bearer {}\", token));\n        }\n```\n\nThe old config field `api_key` is explicitly **not** supported anymore; the CLI is meant to use `git-ai login` (OAuth / device flow) and stored credentials.\n\n### What you still “use” on the server (Supabase)\n\nIn `self-hosted-server/auth.py`, the backend uses **`SUPABASE_ANON_KEY`** (and `SUPABASE_URL`) so the **server** can call Supabase (e.g. inserting device codes). That is a **project** key for your backend, not something end users paste as an “API_KEY” for git-ai:\n\n```52:54:self-hosted-server/auth.py\nSUPABASE_URL = os.environ[\"SUPABASE_URL\"]\nSUPABASE_ANON_KEY = os.environ[\"SUPABASE_ANON_KEY\"]\nBASE_URL = os.environ.get(\"BASE_URL\", \"http://localhost:8000\")\n```\n\n### Direct answer\n\n- **For authenticating git-ai calls to your API:** use the **JWT / access token** from your login flow (`Authorization: Bearer …`). A separate user **`API_KEY` is not used** by this client for that.\n- **For Supabase itself:** Google sign-in still goes through Supabase; the **anon key** (and optionally **service role** for trusted server-only operations) remains on the **server** side. That’s orthogonal to “only Google” — it’s how your app talks to Supabase, not how you replace the user’s Bearer token.\n\nIf by `API_KEY` you mean something else (e.g. a custom header you added on your API gateway), say what layer it’s on and we can map it to this flow.",
