          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "You can **keep removing `API_KEY` from the client** for this setup. Adding more Supabase providers (GitHub, Apple, email magic link, etc.) does **not** mean users suddenly need an API key plus something else for HTTP auth.\n\n### How Supabase treats every “managed auth” path\n\nFor any provider Supabase wires up, the result is the same shape of **session**: an **access token (JWT)** and usually a ��**refresh token**. Your CLI already models that: store credentials, send `Authorization: Bearer <access_token>`, refresh when needed.\n\nSwitching from “Google only” to “Google + GitHub” is a **provider** change in Supabase and in your device/OAuth UI; it is **not** a new credential type like a per-user API key.\n\n### What is *not* a user “API_KEY”\n\n- **`SUPABASE_ANON_KEY` / service role** — project keys for *your server* (or the browser client) talking to Supabase. They do not replace user JWTs and are not something you need to revive as “CLI `api_key`” for each login method.\n- **`Authorization: Bearer …`** — this is how the user proves who they are to *your* API; that stays regardless of provider.\n\n### “Author identity” vs HTTP auth\n\nIn this repo, **git author identity** is about **git commit author** (name/email from `git var` / config), not about authenticating to your backend. It stays independent of whether you use Google, GitHub, or anything else via Supabase.\n\n### When you *would* keep API_KEY in the client\n\nOnly if you **deliberately** want to support a second auth model: long‑lived static keys (B2B, scripts, non-OAuth integrations) **in addition to** OAuth/JWT. That is a **product** choice, not something Supabase forces on you when you add GitHub sign-in.\n\n**Bottom line:** extending Supabase auth to more providers does **not** require users to use `API_KEY`; **JWT + refresh (and Bearer on the wire)** remains the right model, so continuing to remove `API_KEY` keeps the codebase aligned with how Supabase works.",
