          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "Here’s how your **self-hosted server** lines up with **`ApiContext`** in `client.rs`.\n\n## What `ApiContext` sends\n\n```239:247:src/api/client.rs\n        if let Some(api_key) = &self.api_key {\n            request = request.set(\"X-API-Key\", api_key);\n            if let Some(identity) = &self.author_identity {\n                request = request.set(\"X-Author-Identity\", identity);\n            }\n        }\n        if let Some(token) = &self.auth_token {\n            request = request.set(\"Authorization\", &format!(\"Bearer {}\", token));\n        }\n```\n\nSo the client may attach **both** `X-API-Key` / `X-Author-Identity` (if configured) **and** `Authorization: Bearer …` (if logged in).\n\n---\n\n## What the server actually does\n\n### `auth_token` → **Supported** (this is how protected routes work)\n\nProtected handlers use `Depends(require_auth)`, which only accepts a **Bearer** token and validates it with Supabase:\n\n```252:274:self-hosted-server/auth.py\ndef _extract_token(request: Request) -> str:\n    header = request.headers.get(\"Authorization\", \"\")\n    if not header.startswith(\"Bearer \"):\n        raise HTTPException(status_code=401, detail=\"Missing bearer token\")\n    return header[7:]\n...\nasync def require_auth(request: Request):\n    ...\n    token = _extract_token(request)\n    try:\n        user_resp = supabase.auth.get_user(token)\n```\n\nSo the **access token** you get from your device OAuth flow (and refresh) is what the worker endpoints expect—this matches `auth_token` on the client.\n\n### `api_key` (`X-API-Key`) → **Not used for auth**\n\nThere is **no** check of `X-API-Key` anywhere in `self-hosted-server/`. Sending it does not satisfy `require_auth`. If a user only sets an API key in config and never does OAuth, **CAS / metrics calls will get 401** unless something else also sets `Authorization: Bearer …`.\n\n### `author_identity` (`X-Author-Identity`) → **Metadata only (partial)**\n\nIt is **not** used to authenticate. It is only read on CAS upload and stored as `uploaded_by`:\n\n```53:61:self-hosted-server/main.py\n            supabase.table(\"cas_objects\").upsert(\n                {\n                    \"hash\": obj.hash,\n                    \"content\": obj.content,\n                    \"metadata\": obj.metadata,\n                    \"uploaded_by\": request.headers.get(\"X-Author-Identity\"),\n                    \"user_id\": str(user.id),\n                },\n```\n\nSo it aligns with the client comment (“only sent when API key is set”) only in the sense of **optional extra metadata**; the server does not require it and does not tie it to API-key auth.\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\n| `ApiContext` field   | Server support |\n|----------------------|----------------|\n| `auth_token`         | **Yes** — Bearer + Supabase `get_user` |\n| `api_key`            | **No** — header ignored for authentication |\n| `author_identity`    | **Optional CAS field** — not auth |\n\nIf you want **API-key-only** clients against this server, you’d need new server logic (e.g. validate `X-API-Key` against a configured secret and synthesize a service user or bypass RLS in a controlled way). Right now the design is **Bearer (OAuth/Supabase JWT) only** for `/worker/*` except OAuth endpoints themselves.",
